9","Cornwell":"Cornwell, Oxfordshire, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1350–":"1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1385–1455":"1385–1455","–Male":"Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Cornwell":"Cornwell, Oxfordshire, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kayle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Swiss German: variant of   Karl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Karl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Lothar, Erwin, Erhard, Georg, Otto, Bernd, Bernhard, Ernst, Gerhard, Hartmut, Heinz.","German: from the German personal name <i>Karl</i>, from Old High German <i>karl</i> ‘man, husband, freeman’. The popularity of this name and its cognates in central and northern Europe was greatly enhanced by its status as a royal and imperial name; in particular it was bestowed in honor of the Frankish emperor Charlemagne (about 742–814; Latin name <i>Carolus Magnus</i>). This surname is also found in some other European countries, e.g. in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Croatia, but is relatively rare there. See also   Carl   and   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Kayle was born in 1350, in Cornwell, Oxfordshire, England, her father, Ralph Kayl II, was -15 and her mother, Lady Maud Stonard Stonard Of Cornwall, was -15. She had at least 1 son with John Luccombe."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1385–1455":"1385–1455","–Male":"Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Cornwell":"Cornwell, Oxfordshire, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1350–":"1350–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1385–1455":"1385–1455","–Male":"Kuollut","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Cornwell":"Cornwell, Oxfordshire, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1350–":"1350–Décédée","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1385–1455":"1385–1455","–Male":"Décédé","1339–Male":"1339–Décédé","1375–Male":"1375–